A Republican strategy to obstruct Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth and claims that electoral fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people who die from lightning strikes.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Contrary to what happens in Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And in the same vein, a majority of U.S. governments enacted, starting in 2009, new laws that made it difficult to register or vote.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections, which saw the rise of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, in 2011, 180 bills were introduced that restricted the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
New electoral laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, as well as proof of American citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of the ballot, and withdraw their right to vote from citizens with criminal records.
Before the 2006 elections, no state required voters to present a photo ID.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The U.S. Supreme Court in 2008 upheld the constitutionality of Indiana law.
The Republican government hastened to extend the practice to other states.
In recent years, authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike what happens in Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as a Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with those characteristics.
But often, obtaining the required ID costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 do not have a photo ID.
And there's more.
In many states, students, the voters who vote the most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, those same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote for Republican parties to use the documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to file such a request.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit Hispanic voting.
It appears that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers backed in 2011 certain laws that abolished voter registration on the same day of the election in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a support service for voters who would like to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
Measures taken since 2009 brought the registration rate for new voters down in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers passed laws in five other states that favored shorter voting in advance.
For example, in the 2008 Florida election, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-American, while the latter represented only 13% of the state’s voters.
In the case of Hispanics, the same thing happened.
They represent only 11% of the electorate, which is equivalent to 24% of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who represent 76% of the electorate, represent only 46% of citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have fiercely opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
In this regard, Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Attorney’s Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
The damage could be limited in part.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states passed the law requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that with them it is intended to influence the results of 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have passed such laws account for 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty whether these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this regard, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
