The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson generated great shock last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in effect, that this boson is a partaker of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what’s more, it’s about the particle whose existence the standard model predicted: our best or “least bad” explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists it’s not entirely clear that it’s Higgs.
We know without a doubt that there is a new particle and that it looks very much like the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress held in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data is still missing to be completely sure.
Anyway, we assume it's Higgs, because the chances of making mistakes seem small. We'll see what it's about.
There is, in this great world, a widespread and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to break that rule and don’t try too hard, because it will end up being hurt.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: the Pauli exclusion principle, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, roughly speaking, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we find good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
And on the other hand there are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be found in the same place at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Laboratories’ The Particle Adventure website, which, by the way, is extraordinary, the bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, which we will not talk about here, and the “particles of force”, by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, I would point out here, are not the exotic bugs we could believe.
In fact, if he manages to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the "light particle" that acts as the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this “disorder” an electromagnetic wave (of light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing more than a photon; that is, one of the “force-carrying” bosons.
Most Stable Field
The same happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it requires reaching extremely high energies, a bit like an icy pond in which only a thick rock could slide over the surface.
That’s why it takes an immense particle accelerator like CERN (the big hadron collider is a 27 km ring in circumference!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never stick by itself to the door of a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way) do not.
Now, what can all these investigations "contribute"? asks Mrs Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between observations and predictions of the MS.
For their part, many fervently want them to meet, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that plugs certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous deficiencies, such as not proposing any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the Universe (another ups!).
But we have not found such differences in CERN so far.
Consequences
The repercussions of such research in our day-to-day life are hard to predict, but we don’t think we’re wrong to say that it won’t have any.
In the early 1960s, laser pioneers in laboratories did not at all suspect the revolution their work would bring about.
They looked at scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who produced the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, said that at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus".
Imagine...
And in addition, applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light collector in 1969 over the course of his optics research.
Although it was not its original intention at all, this pickup now serves as an “eye” for all the digital devices in the world, which earned it the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
That does not mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC necessarily want to transform our lives, but that you never know...
