Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank their caregivers for not attending to their demands once their pain has been eased thanks to a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful when it comes to treating pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of home palliative care at Grand Montréal, patients do not respond to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors usually resort to palliative sedation, which serves to sleep the patient until the time of his death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can’t pretend we don’t understand that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved disease will have the possibility of having that palliative sedation.
