Bitcoin differs from other systems with virtual currency types such as “credits”, used to advance in a video game and which can be won by playing or can be bought (and even sometimes redeemed).
The social network Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange a central authority controls and deals with changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are both book keepers, verifiers, currency issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses in the form of e-mail.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is electronically signed through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoin changes are contained in the public ledger, which is spread throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge thrown at computers and the winner, a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
It is a phase of file cutting, that is, of transforming a large file into a shorter and unique numerical footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "slicing" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (plus zeroes at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, in order to commit fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very fast (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would be left orphaned, since both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward splits in two regularly, with probability before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to the hundred millionth, which leaves a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in computing power.
The life of the network already has its ups and downs.
Websites offering services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins stolen in deposit.
“The failure used does not affect the same protocol,” says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash has the same flaw.
Prominent actors like Wikipedia reject payments of this kind.
Others, such as the Wordpress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that about 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, the “giant sales” were launched.
“They changed $30,000,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on this currency, believes strongly in the potential of this technology as well as in the network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, equates to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which then come out cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to start up in stores, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
Just provide them with an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of revision of hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
“It will take some time for Bitcoin to take hold, but in 2013 there could be a change,” he predicts.
Moreover, in its report, the ECB plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, if this currency succeeds.
