Generally, I would not like to draw up a comparison without concrete data, but Germany is still a model in some respects, but it cannot be precise on what is better.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of the inspectors?
Of course not, but, I repeat, I don’t like to make these kinds of comparisons.
It must be said that even those countries that we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If not, it would be no benefit to them to collaborate with our office, wouldn't you?
As for the legislation of our country, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean to your Office?
Considering that the validity period of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been expressed in the monitoring actions.
Since we carry out ex post checks, we need to have a certain delay.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparing future controls: we have started a new tool of "detection of non-economic risks", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public tenders, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are rectified and the like.
Do you consider the passage of this law beneficial or, rather, a scam for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope so.
The problem that may arise is that the regulation "hardens" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already under the previous regulations, the controlled persons were bound to the contractor (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes of the regional council), and every law not respected in the field of public procurement meant a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to harden the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system should exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who commit a formal ruling, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this journey begins.
The prime minister has recently declared that the SDG would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called ?varc system, referring to the fact of being autonomous only on paper.
Is the "varc" system prohibited or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits anything, then not even the Prime Minister of the government can prevent the action of the Office that has the obligation to carry out such controls and demand obligations.
You can say, “We change the law and we allow it,” but you can’t say we’ll do it like nothing.
In the law on public procurement, the rules are quite strict as to how to act formally, and this is how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic to exclude the candidate with the best offer for not meeting the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
