Next year we would also like to play at the Bohemian National Hall in New York and I, personally, taking advantage of the fact that we are in the United States, would like to complete it with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not exactly minimalist, so far you have acted for example in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How is the logistics and organization of these trips?
It’s not as hard as it may seem at first glance.
There are five members in an electric wheelchair, the chairs must travel in the luggage compartment and we also carry a lot of weight, the boxes with the instruments...
So far, however, we have managed well. SA and British Airways were perfectly prepared, which still surprises me.
Even in Moscow, from where we recently returned, everything went smoothly.
Thanks to the trips abroad you can compare the different attitudes of society towards the disabled and other aspects.
What have you encountered so far?
In Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, everything works better than here; in Russia we have witnessed that in the east there is a long way to go.
Unlike Prague, Moscow is full of barriers, there it is still uncommon for a person to move around the city center alone in an electric wheelchair.
Something as common as it is, for example, to give preference to someone in a wheelchair in an elevator, there it is not.
Fortunately, a civil association has been created that strives to thematicize the problems of people with disabilities.
In what areas should we take an example from more advanced countries?
There are a lot of things we go behind...
But it is important to mention that the improvement and improvement of the situation always depends on the people it directly affects.
In London and Madrid it is very normal for people with a severe disability to travel on their own in public and be able to go to the service, to the museum, wherever they want to go.
But it is not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to actively participate in social life, in this respect, with The Tap Tap let’s go a little further!
A respectful or barrier-free society is one thing, but when the time comes for eminent athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers to emerge, it will begin to change everything for real.
So far, these are isolated cases of people who have great willpower.
The Tap Tap group is currently very popular, but if you look back a few years, what led you to form the group in 1998?
I entered as an educator in Jedli?k?v ustav, where I had a lot of young people around me who wanted to dedicate themselves to something.
And since I am a musician, I play, among others, the saxophone, I founded an amateur group with a co-worker.
And over time, as our moderator Lá?a Angelovi? says, we got a little out of hand (laughs).
