Argo Movie: If it gets raw, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a group of Islamist students held the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
His release was to be in exchange for the dethroned Shah Mohamed Réza Páhlevi, who after the revolution fled to the United States, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration, the situation offered no positive perspective: throwing the shah overboard could not afford it, as if it did, it would endanger the trust of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within his grasp.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which subsequently intensified further with the failed attempt to release the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government's intervention in negotiations.
In the U.S., his fate caused a wave of solidarity and encouragement against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck thematicizes an episode of this story, which reaped a small success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a difficult journey, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian embassy.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, for this helped a covert story an extravagant point: they came out with Canadian passports, as members of the film crew examining the location in the country for the shooting of a sci-fi overproduction.
Combination of genres
The plan drawn up by “exfiltration” expert Toni Mendez required the collaboration of Hollywood.
To make the lie seem true, it was written about the film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production society even had a real office.
Details about the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a singular combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a hoax (an example may be the Ocean's Eleven series).
On the one hand, we find well-documented sequences of Tehran. In the sequence of credits are shown emblematic photographs of the era of events, which were shaped in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes a little lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And in addition, scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions: costumed men analyzing the situation at the negotiating table, in the corridors of the office, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been mocked, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is her third feature film, after "Goodbye Little, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it’s Affleck’s first film in which the action doesn’t take place in the city of Boston, where he grew up.
Also, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed the directors of old films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck proves it in Argo, where Tehran “wheels” in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of the real events. The introductory sequence of the embassy takeover is impressive for its synoptic capacity that, at the same time, conveys the emotion of the confusion and lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, the story takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the impostor team at the Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story does not offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
And it does quite well. Sometimes it adds something to the reality: here everything doesn’t go so elegantly (the scene where the crisis looms at Tehran airport, the diversion of a call to America and the unbridled search behind its track become madness).
The weakness of Argo is the out of control that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are not, much less, the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck’s film loses a bit of a dramatic trait, but it is a film that can be followed with a moderate interest, appreciating its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 70s.
But if it collapses, that will be difficult.
As an evocation of a real story and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of the secret services can be, it is enough.
