The architectural studio MVRDV proves that the real adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the newly finished "mountain of books"- 2 photos
“I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, and finally there’s something interesting to see,” says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby passing by.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician at a large company located near the library, points out: "Moreover, the building is beautiful."
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have internet, tablets and e-books.
No one likes to go into those old-fashioned libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town on the outskirts of Rotterdam that barely deserves a short visit, boasts the dubious honor of having set a record for forgetting.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this embarrassing situation, some years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and copy the seven fictitious bridges that appear represented on the euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that’s how policymakers decided that there was only one way to improve statistics: you had to build a library!
Winy Maas, of Dutch architectural firm MVRDV, a master of the art of bar charts and responsible for fun buildings as well as cynics, took the subject with his usual serenity and appeared at the presentation of the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked perplexed around and shrugged, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size into a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here is my proposal for Spijkenisse’s mountain of books, the so-called Boekenberg.”
Nine years later, the €30 million mountain rises to its intended place.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of residential and townhouse buildings.
At the beginning of November the mountain of books was awarded with the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the small town without history, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white facade one would rather intuit a dairy farm, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long road to the book
The first impression is that it is a book paradise under a cheeseburger.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountainous massif, but true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to merge with its topography every step of its climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to embrace with the view, the annealed brick floor and elegant streetlights unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
When you look up, you can see the park benches, the dogs and the boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally bookcases are arranged along the façade and in the center opens a huge dark room that is usually uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
What we have done is put the classic spatial configuration upside down and take the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserves the black shelves that assume the functions of wall cladding, parapet and railing at the same time.
Sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even the most everyday architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, project manager in the city of Spijkenisse.
And that’s how one day, on a Friesian farm, we stumble upon the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years now, in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, a thin plastic fabric has been used as a base for holding crop roots.
It is an inexpensive and efficient material.
This fine fabric lasts two seasons and is then discarded.
For the library this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, to obtain plates four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a mix of new car and sneaker.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but you can also enjoy tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant environment while maintaining adequate atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a New Soul
“Although it’s hard to believe given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project when it comes to ecology,” says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling is obtained from geothermal energy.
Even though the mountain of books is located under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden enclosures located transversely to the glass facade serve to give shade and absorb most of the sun’s rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is about automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical IT worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has been there too.
Likewise, Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, has visited the library, calling the Boekenberg the Spijkenisse’s “late soul.”
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
This way it is intended, for the moment, to fill the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its full archive; it currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept has gone deep.
The shelves are full.
“There’s nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
“I think that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows that your book is part of the library.
Even if it's just there to adorn.
In this way, the MVRDV studio has achieved great success in that reigning discipline that in specialized slang is known as "creation of an identity".
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
No matter how young and uneducated you are.
Finally a starting point to shape your identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a more protagonist role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-Europe relations, this puts Berlin in a rather dangerous diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany implied that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories observer status of the United Nations.
Eventually, however, Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, due to the special relationship that unites the country with Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time, I don’t think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising that took place in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because at the moment he is reorienting his foreign policy, moving away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
Therefore, the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they’re still teasing what their role will be, but they’ve already started the road to a “normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to countries like France or Britain.
What does “normal” foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy finds a strong motivation in economic policy, that is, in exports and in its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are somewhat different from those of other great powers, and for this reason Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position taken regarding the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason she must be careful and not alienate herself from Arab public opinion or Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I wouldn’t give it that much importance because it’s not a totally one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a key role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the United States by refraining from voting on important decisions such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position enjoys an enormous degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not believe that there has been such a drastic breakup as in the case of Libya.
Germany may have earned a certain amount of respect.
After all, all this has only shown that it is a country that they take seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, there are different opinions about the Palestinian initiative.
Instead, the U.S. has clearly expressed its support for a veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the U.S. and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of American domestic policy.
I think the Obama administration secretly shows a great deal of understanding towards the European position.
But, because of the political situation here, it is clear that the government cannot publicly defend this position.
I believe that the true disparity of opinion does not really have the magnitude attributed to it.
If we look at the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not at all excited about the policy he develops.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of its main partners in the EU, on the other?
I think that’s exactly what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and homogeneous European policy, but that is not the case.
