Behind this name is a name officially registered in China but that has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection as long as the true eponyms do not file a lawsuit.
And even then it is not clear that they are going to be given the reason.
“Foreigners are finding it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at the Taylor Wessing law firm specializing in protection rights violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes to my table.
Imitators simply add a couple of letters to be able to register their marks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada is registered Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied in the same way, as has happened to the sports goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens an archive in which she keeps seats from the Beijing trademark office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the Zegna DF Puma brand, an artificial name that also used the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In the big cities there are large warehouses of several floors dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, Pattloch’s cases are of a different kind, and on behalf of his clients, he fights against the fact that the trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a denomination that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or accompanying brand.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
It refers to women who have “fished” a rich man.
Chinese authorities don’t feel guilty
“It’s detrimental to the business, you have to fight it,” Pattloch demands.
“The brand makes waters, the monopolistic position disappears and the damage suffered by the image is enormous.”
The financial losses and procedural costs of the affected sectors are millions, especially in the case of iconic luxury products.
According to market analysis firm CLSA, with a volume of 15 billion euros a year, China is, in size, the third largest market for luxury goods and the fastest growing.
However, achieving the cancellation of registrations of doubtful legality in the registration of trademarks is complicated and also involves a lot of money.
Processes can last up to nine years and the result is uncertain.
Pattloch speaks of cases in which the court dismissed a lawsuit because it had been so long that the name object of the lawsuit had already become a "market reality".
“If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay money to the plagiarizer because the process has damaged his brand in China,” Pattloch said.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the best-known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that has recently been absorbed by the German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That’s why today the Chinese can still use an emblem very similar to the Mercedes star.
Volvo buyer Geely initially used a blue-and-white logo that was largely reminiscent of BMW; the matter was settled in court and Geely had to modify it.
Clothing maker Lacoste lost in China against imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo depicted a crocodile looking in the opposite direction from the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO brand office in Beijing acknowledges that in 2010 they had difficulties due to shortages of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, “the work emergency situation returned to normal.”
In this way, the number of unprocessed claims processes has been reduced by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75% more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 claims remain pending resolution.
Fighting this costs a lot of money.
As is usual in China, the numbers are surprising.
Last year, the CTMO registered more than 1.4 million trademark protection applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
It would be a new record and means China is leading the list of new entries worldwide for the 10th year in a row, according to the trademark office.
This also seems to be the case with the number of valid logos, which amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan in entitlements would have been collected.
In other words, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting against this costs a lot of money, as demonstrated by the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For more than seven years, the group has been fighting in court against a Chinese impersonator.
While the Germans have managed to stop the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts,
The imitator has secured Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
“We ourselves have provoked this situation because in Germany surnames are not protected,” said Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The CTMO trademark office also dismissed the Munich appeal.
In the next two instances, Freudenberg was right, but the opposing side is still fighting today.
You have to be very careful
Now the case has reached the doors of the Superior Court of Justice, where it remains pending resolution.
Wentzler is confident in being able to resolve the issue favourably and praises the professionalism of the courts.
However, it also states that “the procedure is extremely expensive, both in terms of money and time.”
It is difficult to estimate internal costs; the business archive has had to review files up to a hundred years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the opposing party a “six-figure sum in euros” with the aim of reaching a friendly deal, but it was unsuccessful.
“This shows how much we care,” Wentzler says.
The dangers lurking in the Far East even threaten to affect Europe.
Specifically, if imitators secure there the rights to unprotected trademarks.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register in Germany the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather products.
The group has long since abandoned this commercial field, yet managed to prevent registration.
“You have to be very careful,” Wentzler says.
Both he and lawyer Pattloch advise German companies to be extremely cautious when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international trademark law, but what needs to be done is "register everything that may be susceptible to protection in China", as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the topic can be much more expensive than a simple registration.
In fact, should Freudenberg lose the last round of his particular battle, then he would have to pay the opposing party license fees in his own name, as Wentzler explains.
