However, we are in the southernmost part of Azerbaijan; from here the border with Iran is only a few kilometers away.
Here live the "Talyshi", a people of which not much is known, apart from that they perfectly dominate Persian and Azeri and that they are very long-lived.
Our final destination is Lerik.
This small town boasts a perhaps too massive architecture designed in the Soviet era and that does not seem to fit completely into such a picturesque mountain landscape.
European tourists barely reach this place, as the road from the Azerbaijani capital, Baku, turns out to be too heavy.
To travel the 323 kilometers that separate the two urban centers, it takes eight hours because the road is one-way.
The amazing wealth that the country enjoys thanks to the oil of the Caspian Sea has not yet reached this hidden region.
However, Pilata Fatulayeva (48) is convinced that Lerik has what it takes to become a tourist attraction.
“Baku became famous in May on the occasion of the Eurovision Song Contest and next year we will be celebrating the World’s Oldest People Festival,” says Fatulayeva.
It is the director of the Museum of Longevity, perhaps the only one that exists in the world.
Here is documented the lives of eight dozen talyshis of the place who have surpassed 100 years of age. Fatulayeva points to a black and white image.
This is my grandfather, who lived 120 years.
His son died at the age of 136.
The museum’s undisputed star, however, is sheepherder Oirali Müslümov, who appears to have lived 168 years.
However, there is no birth certificate to certify it.
And if we take into account that the older documented man lived 122 years, it seems that the age of Müslümov is quite suspicious.
“He was born in the region in 1805 and died in 1973,” Fatulayeva explains.
The man was married three times and had 23 children. Apparently he still had time to conceive one more daughter at the age of 136.
Have you, then, been wrong about your age in a couple of decades?
