The Norwegian rakfisk: the most smelly fish in the world?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the success of the country bears any relation to its craving for a highly smelly fish?
Take a series of overly cured cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a mountain of dirty, wet football clothes.
Leave it there for a week.
You will then be able to smell the paralyzing aroma of rakfisk, one of the delicacies of Norway.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
The landscape is spectacular and that smell, always present, floats in the air.
Rakfisk is salted trout that is allowed to ferment in water for up to a year, depending on how smelly you prefer.
As it gets darker and colder, Norwegians flock to a festival held here in Fagernes, dedicated to this most, so to speak, captivating delicacy.
“You eat raw and then drink a glass of aquavit from a drink,” says Havard Halvarsen, a city fireman who is also known as the “General of Rakfisk,” who is in charge of organizing the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is stored in small cubes and drinking from a drink significant amounts of the drink.
“Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk,” Havard says.
Drinking can kill the smell.
I try some pieces.
If you can avoid passing it close to your nose, it’s not bad; it’s not unlike a portion of sushi that’s traveled a few miles by bus.
Rakfisk is a product that comes from a very different time, when poverty plagued Norway and before there was refrigeration, fish was stored during the fall immersed in water and salt in airtight barrels.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is already well fermented, it is taken out and, evidently with the senses inactive due to alcohol, it is eaten.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and emigrated mainly to the United States.
Currently, the population is growing rapidly; more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high wages and a complete system of social services.
A stream of people from Sweden, the old rival and even not too much richer than Norway, arrives in this country to work.
Rakfisk is considered an important, essential, but rather smelly part of Norway’s past.
It is among the most expensive dishes that can be purchased.
But, in fact, everything is expensive. A beer cane or a sandwich cost you a whopping 10€ ($14) each.
Norway doesn’t usually appear on the international news agenda and most Norwegians like that.
Here people are still unwilling to pronounce the name of Anders Breivik, the far-right racist who shot and killed 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as “the July 22 event.”
It is very difficult for the Norwegians to believe that in their peaceful country one of their own could commit such cruelty and murder.
Behind much of Norway’s current wealth lies the growth, since the early 1970s, of one of the world’s largest oil and gas industries.
“But oil isn’t the only reason we’re doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress, as she goes past rakfisk trays and which, with its long blonde mane and striking blue eyes, represents the image of Norwegian well-being.
“We are, as you say, wise people.”
His English, like that of most people in this country, is impeccable.
"We don't like to brag, we don't like ostentation."
Norway has managed its oil wealth very cautiously; everything except a small percentage of the money from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone was wasting money they didn’t have during the years leading up to the worldwide financial crisis, Norway kept the wallet tightly closed.
“As long as we can ski in winter and go hiking in summer, we’re happy,” says Anna.
"And eat rakfisk," he adds with an unwrapped load.
I’m in the snow queuing to eat something; I’ve had enough rakfisk.
Now a moose burger is certainly something different and quite juicy to taste.
But at night, that smelly fish comes back.
The hotel where I stay is one of the many places where a rakfisk dinner is held in which the diners vote for the best fish, or perhaps the one that tests the nostrils the most.
A TV has connected live with a birdie-wearing presenter who is surrounded by rakfisk dishes.
It looks like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here's our score, Havard."
There is laughter and applause.
A man falls from the chair, perhaps defeated by the aquavit.
Or maybe it's the vapours of all that fish.
Mexico: Enrique Peña Nieto faces a tough start
As Mexico’s incoming President Enrique Peña Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant looks at the challenges facing the new president and the different expectations of his population.
Traffic in Mexico City is especially bad right now.
In a city that, under the best circumstances, is already congested, a steel fence has been installed since Monday that cuts several of the main roads that lead to the city and that is causing enormous chaos on the roads.
The goal, however, was not to prevent workers from reaching their workplace, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico’s new president, Enrique Peña Nieto, will host the presidential band and take over the nation.
He faces a complicated task.
Mexico has been doing well during the outgoing government of Felipe Calderón, but the country is immersed in a war against drug trafficking that has already claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
“My administration has the great commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence,” Mr. Peña Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
“I’m going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve that goal.”
Before coordinating with the president of the United States, Mr. Peña’s previous political experience was as governor of his home state, Mexico.
A highly populated and fast-growing state, surrounding the capital; opinions about the new leader are divided into this territory in which he used to move.
A sincere man
In the bucolic city of Valle del Bravo, for example, he is fondly remembered.
Its residents credit it with the growth of on-site tourism and infrastructure construction.
To get to the city you can drive along one of the new roads of Mr. Peña Nieto, which is a huge improvement compared to the cracked roads and full of bumps that have been rehabilitated.
You can also see plaques with his name at the entrance of a modern sports hall and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We are confident that he can make real and lasting change," says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a deputy for Mr. Peña Nieto's party, the PRI.
