However, on the other side of the state that is not the impression that many people have on their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
Hidden beneath elevated stretches of highway is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems of the municipality are also harsh and urban.
Earlier this year, the military was asked to help fight neighborhood drug gangs and violence against women is especially serious.
In a desert plot next to a garbage dump, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been abandoned in just the last two years.
More than 1,000 women were killed in the state of Mexico while Mr. Peña Nieto was governor, a far higher rate than that of Ciudad Juarez, unfortunately famous for its violence and a place that is synonymous with the murder of innocent women.
Critics of Mr. Peña Nieto say, at best, that he failed to address the problem of femicide while in office.
Most critics accuse their administration of turning a blind eye.
In a concrete house, typical of the deteriorating neighborhood, Irinea Buendía has to make efforts to contain tears while showing me photographs of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the facts, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes her partner murdered her.
“When I arrived at her house, it seemed as if her body had been cleaned,” recalls Mrs. Buendía.
“There were signs that she had been beaten and rigor mortis had already appeared.”
As her mother recounts the story, a photograph of Mariana looks from the walls, next to a cross in which she reads a single word: Justice.
However, that’s exactly what the family says he’s been denied.
“State authorities have treated me like I was a gossipy old woman, a troublemaker, a grievance.
What they want is that one simply accepts what they say and shuts up.”
“But that can’t be the case when there have been so many irregularities and so much negligence,” he says.
The presidential band that President Peña Nieto will receive on Saturday will be accompanied by a huge responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by violent crimes in Mexico over the past six years and the new president has pledged to prioritize them during his tenure.
“I hope he’s the same kind of president he was when he was governor,” says PRI Olvera’s deputy in Valle del Bravo.
However, that is precisely what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear the most.
Bradley Manning did not report ill-treatment, prosecutors say
Prosecutors try to deal with allegations of abuse of Bradley Manning during his time in prison
The trial focuses on Manning’s time at Quantico Military Prison in Virginia.
The defense wants the case dismissed on the grounds that Manning’s incarceration was severe.
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to report the ill-treatment he now claims he suffered while in military detention.
During the prosecution’s interrogation of Manning at a pretrial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein said that records of weekly visits by officers of the unit Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaint about the treatment he was receiving.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing following the defence's request that the case be dismissed given that his imprisonment had been harsh and that it had already entailed sufficient punishment, came a day after Manning had testified that he had thought of committing suicide while in detention.
The army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while serving in Iraq.
Later, WikiLeaks published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
At Friday’s hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that officers filled out after visits to Manning during his arrest at Quantico military prison, where he was held in maximum detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers would have asked Manning questions and written down his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had rated the caretaker’s treatment as “excellent” and the treatment he received at the facility as a whole as “very professional.”
The forms show no allegations of ill-treatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that officials visiting him had discussed those issues and indicated that they would be addressed, but that they did not record those issues on the record.
“They wrote ‘no incidents’ (after I’ve talked about the issues) but that doesn’t necessarily mean I wouldn’t have mentioned any problems,” Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not reported the treatment he received during the January 2011 meeting with a council tasked with examining the suicide intentions he had expressed on a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the “injury prevention” regime under which he was.
The military said it had been placed under that restrictive regime, which is one degree below that of surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure its protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was fine and to stop being under injury prevention... so they could enjoy what, in my view, is a better quality of life,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison located at the Marine base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and once lost consciousness due to the heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced only to Camp Arafjon, to that cage," Manning said Thursday.
“I thought I was going to die in that cage.”
Manning claimed that, once moved to Quantico, he spent most days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he tried to move all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning said he always had a light coming from outside pointing at his eyes as he slept.
He said that if the caretakers couldn’t see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn around again.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint in January 2011 about Manning’s treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he had made in Thursday’s statement that, after being forced one night to sleep naked in his Quantico cell, he was forced during a morning count to stand naked in front of jailers and other inmates.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge’s interrogation on Friday, Manning said he deduced from the order given to him by the jailer that he should drop the blanket with which he could have been covered, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he had told the officer that he could have used the rubber band of his underwear or his slippers to injure himself but had not.
Manning testified that night his underwear, flip flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers are hopeful that the judge will at least take into account his experiences during his time in prison and drastically reduce his sentence if he is convicted on the war council, which is scheduled to start early next year.
The defense said it planned to have Manning plead guilty to misdemeanors and defend other allegations deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has argued that Manning was held in accordance with the rules of application to any detainees who are in maximum custody at Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, illegally posting information on the Internet, leaking national defense information, and theft of property or public records.
If convicted of all charges, he could face life in prison.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis
He says many were forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities.
Mexicans tend to criticize those who left; they say they remind Mexicans of those difficult times
Navarrette comments that Mexican-Americans find themselves trapped between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, he had barely gotten down the esplanade and arrived in the immigration processing zone and was already totally confused.
Posters pointed the way to two queues: one for "Mexicans" and one for "Foreigners."
I stayed there for a few seconds not sure where I should go.
Having grown up in Central California, I’ve been called “Mexican” all my life.
It’s ethnic shorthand, the same way my friends in Boston refer to themselves as “Irish” or my friends in New York call themselves “Italians.”
I later decided on “Mexican-American.”
But this was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather’s homeland, shorthand or scripts were not necessary.
He was simply American.
I speak Spanish well enough to handle myself during an interview in this language.
But I don’t have the level of vocabulary of a native and I can’t get rid of my American accent.
So I took my U.S. passport and got in the queue of foreigners.
I thought of that moment this week when Mexican President-elect Enrique Peña Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
The agenda of the day, as always when the leaders of these two countries meet, was: immigration, drugs and trade.
Peña Nieto was also eager to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, one of the reasons why a Mexican is as likely to stay in Mexico as he is to venture to the United States.
It wants to partner with the United States and Canada and create a European-style trade bloc in North America.
In addition, Peña Nieto promised to continue fighting the drug cartels in Mexico, although he did not give details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to cede half of their territory to pistol tip.
But for Mexicans, who think in centuries, not in minutes, the elements that remind them are everywhere.
So the moment a U.S. official says anything that brings the slightest criticism to Mexico, you start to hear complaints, both in the press and among the Mexican elite, about how Americans are usurping the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the sons of Moctezuma stand up at war.
And yet, for Mexico, the truly challenging relationship is the one they have with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
Are we talking about resentment?
There's a lot.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for whom it is not.
The only reason there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that, somewhere on our family tree, there was one person, perhaps the father or mother or one of the grandparents, who was closed the door of opportunity in Mexico and had to march north.
And most of the time that person fit a certain profile: dark skin, a low level of education, from a poor village, etc.
We are their descendants and we are loyal to them.
Mexico not.
And even though we may be living the American dream now, having gone to good schools and had good jobs, we can never lose sight of what we are living, the American dream, not the Mexican one.
Sometimes our identity may be unclear, but our loyalty is.
It's for the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many of the Mexicans belonging to the ruling class elite do not like it.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look at us over the shoulder as if we were from a lower category that is not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
In his view, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families hadn’t failed in Mexico, they wouldn’t have left.
And now we would not find ourselves trapped behind this silk curtain, living well in the United States but still as lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and came to the United States legally as a child, reminds me that there is this tension between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because the former know more solidly who they are and the latter this bothers them.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she considers herself part of the two countries.
Meanwhile, many Mexican-Americans I know feel they are not part of either.
We love to hear the Mexican group Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best of each country, but you are not rooted in any of them.
They see us in Mexico as Americans.
In the United States, we are considered Mexicans.
Now, to further complicate things, from what I learned during my trip, some Mexican leaders and some intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as improvised “ambassadors” of Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our American comrades how fantastic it is to visit that country and we would pressure political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure.
That's not gonna happen.
There's too much grudge.
And, with wage inequality, rampant corruption and drug violence, many of us aren’t so sure it’s a fantastic country.
I'm afraid you're going to be alone with this idea, friends.
That's fair.
If some Mexicans are still unprepared to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resentful of how their relatives were treated far less time ago.
Hmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old Battles, New Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas may well be an unlikely basis for peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed that seems to indicate that any hope is in vain.
Amid useless and usual discussions about who started first, piles of buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed and, for the first time, missiles from Gaza have fallen near Tel Aviv, the metropolis of Israel, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But, even though Israelis and Palestinians seem to be anchored in their old conflict, everything around them in the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring has left everything to pieces whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have been caught up in the regional uproar.
Perhaps this makes their struggle even more bloody than before.
However, there is reason to think that their deadly deadlock could unravel.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism seems very difficult to justify.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on Nov. 21 is maintained, this week’s clashes have reinforced hawks on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to withdraw, even though Gaza has received a good beating.
And despite killing some of its leaders and putting pressure on Gaza’s 1.7 million inhabitants in one of the most miserable and populous corners of the planet, Israel has failed to wipe out Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently ruled by its relentless rivals of Fatah, the most moderate Palestinian faction.
In addition, Hamas leaders could conclude that time is playing in their favor.
As Islamists have been gaining influence throughout the Arab world, Hamas has made rich and powerful friendships.
Turkey, a resurgent regional power that had previously been Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has embraced the cause of Hamas, as has Qatar, one of the Gulf’s wealthiest and most dynamic states.
Exultant Hamas members say the Islamist crescent is encircling Israel, from Lebanon to the north, where the Hezbollah militia party dominates, to Syria, where increasingly Islamist rebels could topple Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies are threatening the king.
Especially on the southern flank of Israel, the growth of the Muslim Brotherhood led by President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and fundamental of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled in Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, did not have much time for Hamas.
Instead, the Muslim Brotherhood is a cousin to Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic actions, it is possible that Hamas will emerge as a protagonist that cannot be excluded, not even Israel and the United States.
Meanwhile, Israel’s hard wing will draw the opposite conclusion.
As far as the military issue is concerned, they have put Hamas in its place.
Israel’s Iron Dome anti-missile system has proven its effectiveness and many of Hamas’ missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will sleep more peacefully... for a while.
As for diplomacy, the United States is stronger than ever; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for initiating the latest wave of violence.
Above all, Israel has prospered, especially under Benjamin Netanyahu, a prime minister who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although the rockets fired from Gaza have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has not had too many suicide bombers, partly thanks to the barrier that erodes the West Bank, the main piece of territory aspiring to become a state of Palestine, and protects Jewish settlements that continue to increase even though, under international law, they are illegal.
Mr. Netanyahu, whose Likud party has joined an even harder-line group led by Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the January 22 election, is in a good position.
Why pamper those Palestinian twisted people by giving them a state of their own?
If they really ruled in the West Bank, wouldn’t they fire rockets just like their compatriots did in Gaza?
It is better to have them behind that wall and give them a good blow if they raise their heads.
Perhaps the hard wing is imposed, although the Arab spring could alter their calculations.
Even if Islamists who seize power in Egypt and elsewhere do not have too much appreciation for Israel, their priority will be to address internal difficulties.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the superpower of the area will hardly help the new Arab governments to improve their economies.
That the pragmatic Mr. Morsi has worked with Barack Obama to get a ceasefire is a good omen and could mark the beginning of something.
Israelis should also think long-term.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination means creating a powder keg that will one day explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state and demographics worsen the situation as the Arab population increases.
The bloody missions against Gaza every two to three years to reject Hamas will pay an ever-increasing diplomatic toll.
Both sides need a push from people outside the conflict.
The solution remains the one advocated by sensible people on both sides, the majority of the outside world and this newspaper: two states and Israel’s cession of territory for security reasons.
The hope, small in the short term, is that the ceasefire will give a little more momentum to the people of others who are fighting for this cause.
Egypt, which must start curbing the entry of arms into Gaza, along with Turkey and Qatar, is in an unprecedented situation to convince Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, with land exchanges and a shared Jerusalem.
Arabs foreign to the issue should also pressure Hamas and Fatah to unite.
That would contribute more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the imminent attempt to obtain a virtual state category at the UN.
Mr. Obama also has an important role in getting Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he failed to present his own peace plan.
Again in the White House, he seems just as reluctant to devote his attention to it.
This is a deplorable vision of the future.
A stable Middle East is of vital interest to the United States.
This implies a peace agreement between Israel and Palestine.
The Tobacco Packaging Act comes into force in Australia
Warnings about the risks of smoking and diseased body parts appear on green-coloured out-of-boxes, which are the same for all tobacco brands
Australia’s pioneering tobacco and generic packaging law comes into force and replaces logos and brand colors with a wrapper of olive green, gruesome images of diseased body parts and depictions of children and babies sick from being children of smoking parents.
With the exception of the different images and sanitary warnings, the only difference between the cartridges, mandatory since Saturday, are the names of the brands, all printed in a small font type.
This is the world’s strictest regime for tobacco packaging.
