In a constantly connected world, it’s not so bad to get a little bored.
During this year’s Thanksgiving celebrations, I unexpectedly had to spend five hours at an airport because the plane we were flying on had a mechanical problem and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
So I had a lot of time to think about boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Spending half a day at an airport waiting for a flight to arrive is quite boring, even if you have means to be entertained, such as books, magazines or iPhones, without forgetting the duty-free shops.
But more and more academics and child development experts are praising the benefits of boredom.
According to them, it’s okay for us and our children to get bored from time to time.
Being bored forces the brain to look for interesting options and may foster creativity.
Since most of us are currently connected to this or that screen, we don’t experience the benefits of boredom.
So should we willingly accept boredom?
Yeah.
And no.
But, we'll talk about it later.
First, like many people, I assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of the book "Boredom: A Lively History" published in 2011 by Yale University Press states, it is not.
“In fact, the story of boredom is very extensive,” he says.
In the walls of Pompeii there are graffiti in Latin on the boredom dating from the first century A.D.
We must also consider how we define boredom.
“The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in many different ways,” says John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After examining the published research and presenting the idea to a 100-strong discussion group, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of “desiring, but not being able, to participate in an activity that fills you.”
He says the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person doesn’t do something but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do something.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is “the alteration of the attention process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly.”
Boredom can sound terribly similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that while they may be related, people who are bored tend to see the problem as a matter of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed consider the problem to be their own.
Sometimes we think we are bored, when what actually happens to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In his study “The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention,” published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading a journal article.
Some groups heard in the adjoining room a full-volume TV show that kept no relationship, others heard it with low volume, so it was barely noticeable, while the third group did not listen to the audio at any time.
The group that listened to the show with the low volume showed more boredom than the other two groups; they struggled to concentrate, but weren’t sure why and blamed it on boredom.
“When you try to focus on a difficult or interesting task, attentional disturbance can lead to boredom,” said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study’s authors.
“On the other hand, when you’re doing something boring, like detecting defective parts in a manufacturing line, music that distracts you can help you not get bored.”
“In fact, we currently know that moving around or making scribbles, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help combat it as they make that person physically more alert.”
“Research shows that those children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to stand still,” says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it’s like to get bored at some point: the delay of a plane, a monotonous speaker, an especially boring movie.
But some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To help measure it, some researchers developed in the 1980s a “boring trend scale.”
The scale includes issues like “many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous” and “there are so many things that interest me that I don’t have time to do everything.”
Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, says that using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored more often than girls, and specifically need more external stimulation and more varied.
But, in general, teenagers are a type of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day through a search.
He found that 32 percent of teens said they were bored while at school or doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when they were not at school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the current boredom rates, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But what he did know was that “adolescence is a time when boredom reaches its highest levels,” largely because both children and teens aren’t given much control over what they want to do.
So, back to my question from the beginning: is it good to be bored?
Sometimes it is not, because, taken to the extreme, it can cause us to expose ourselves to absurd physical risks, such as betting or falling into substance use as a method to combat it, as evidenced by research.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this issue for more than two decades.
“ Boredom is the brain’s way of telling you you should be doing something else,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn’t always know what’s most appropriate.
If you are bored and use that energy to play the guitar or cook, that will satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, it may satisfy you in the short term, but not in the long term.
“So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he may no longer be bored, but he will not have learned to entertain himself or dose himself,” says Professor Fenske.
And “that ability to be dosed applies to other situations,” he points out.
Your child not only learns to entertain themselves, but learns to control themselves better in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But we shouldn’t be too critical of him either.
Our goal should be, rather, to feel comfortable away from the constant noise of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
“In our view, we need to get more bored, but boredom is too distressing and disturbing a desire to relate to something worthwhile,” he says.
He points out that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy a dead time.
“In an environment where we’re constantly overstimulated,” he says, “it’s hard to find ways to focus our attention when the noise stops.”
