There are people for whom their work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of 400 miners who make a living taking sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he has to descend every day to the bottom of his crater, where the sulfurous gas emanating from the bowels of the Earth solidifies upon coming into contact with the air.
After plucking large sulfur rocks, which in total weigh about 70 kilos, he carries them in two baskets of bamboo that he carries on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
They are only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters above sea level, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb at turtle’s pace, keeping their balance and tentatively measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall down the precipice.
