UNASUR Summit ends without making the Lima Declaration public
The 6th Presidential Summit of the South American Union of Nations (UNASUR) concluded today in Peru without the Declaration of Lima, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven attending presidents, being made public.
Efe repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but sources from the Foreign Ministry and the Presidency initially indicated that they were going to deliver it after the closure, but later stated that at some point it will be published on the Peruvian government website.
When consulted by the text, they pointed out that the content had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during a brief statement to the press.
Journalists’ access to Summit information was restricted at all times.
During the day, only the soundless video of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated among the reporters was delivered by press spokespersons from some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, although not Peruvian.
The only document released during the day was the list of assistant presidents, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the Presidency of Peru sent an email to the media with the “final declaration” of the summit, but it is Humala’s pronouncement, not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South America-Arab Countries Summit (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being insistently demanded by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration that they had previously announced was also not broadcast.
On the official website of ASPA it can be corroborated that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities made efforts to ensure that transmission systems were insured for all journalists but limited the collection of information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to accept a ruling by the Hague Court that settles a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (CIJ), which begins Monday in The Hague to hear the allegations of both parties, in the process that Lima presented against Santiago.
"We will abide by and execute the sentence that defines the differences we are bringing to this international court today," Humala said.
“Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country that respects international law, the peaceful settlement of disputes, treaties and international courts,” Piñera added, handshaking Humala alongside the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of both presidents that they will submit to the ICJ came after Colombia this week denounced the Bogotá Pact for which it had agreed to submit to the rulings of that international court, following a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered seriously wrong.
The summit was held with the inconsistencies of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was in charge of opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit, shortly after noon in Lima.
The president read the final document in which he reported that 16 agreements were adopted and the lines of action were set for 31 projects among South American countries for a total of $17 billion in investments.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR countries will take "important steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship for which we are expanding the residency agreements."
He said actions are being promoted to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, low-cost internet access in all corners of South America, and jointly and efficiently address the risks of natural disasters."
With a Europe in crisis, “economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must serve to expand our productive matrix and envision a better future for our peoples,” Humala added.
“We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas ... uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” the Peruvian president said in a message read.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located on the transversal axes of their territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he gave no further details.
Also, the final document mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve for his reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," from which he is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region of prosperity and peace, and for good neighbourly relations, was another of the issues underlined by the summit.
In this regard, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to deal respectfully with the maritime dispute following a ruling by the ICJ, questioned by Bogotá.
"Tomorrow (Saturday) I may have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
“We are going to review all these roads, they are not exclusive, even the treaty with Nicaragua is going to require a conversation with Nicaragua,” he said.
"With President Ortega I hope to be able to tell him to handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos said.
Santos and Ortega would meet Saturday in Mexico where they plan to attend the takeover of that country’s new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Also, as part of the summit, the bloc’s defense ministers previously met to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defense in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru has the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
