Start a course that explores the "End of the World"
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charme decided to teach a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible hook: The end of the “long countdown” of the Mayan Calendar, December 21, to which many people have clung as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what awaited him in the next couple of months: Cataclysmic Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal cliff that some have called “deudamagedon” and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where end-time Christian theorists believe the Apocalypse will begin.
“I didn’t realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever,” Charme told students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If you look at what has been going on in the world today as if we were 30 days away and counting, this has been a really good time.
And remember that bad is good for those of apocalyptic mindset.
And he's not the only professor offering courses on the "end of the world" this semester, in theory the last in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker is teaching the course “Media, Culture and the End of the World.”
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We look at why these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month the students analyzed films with apocalyptic themes and explored how they compare to real-life examples.
“I have tried to inform students about what is possible, probable, credible and impossible,” Vacker said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, have teamed up to teach a course, titled “The End of the World.”
“We didn’t add ‘2012’ to always have the option to teach the course again, in case the world isn’t over,” Restall said.
Despite the “imminent ruin,” students must study, generate projects, and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the Apocalypse, which leaves students no choice but to work “until the very night the world is supposed to end,” Restall said.
The courses were quite popular.
“It was saturated in two hours,” Restall said of his high-average student course, which was filled with 35 students.
We received emails for weeks and weeks before the start of the semester from people asking if there was still room.
Students, on the other hand, say that the course is one of the most interesting.
“It’s fascinating to see what people do to console themselves,” said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old career student in Religion and Sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden.
The apocalyptic, secular or religious mentality is only a matter of consolation or the absence of consolation.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, said he saw all the apocalyptic movies.
“I had never heard of a class that could teach that,” he said.
I enjoy it.
But no student interviewed – let alone a professor – said they believed in the December 21 expiration date.
“Our first project dealt with Mayan prophecy and we somehow discredited it,” said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior at Temple and West Chester.
The Maya never predicted the end of the world; it’s just a key point on the calendar, Restall said.
But he noted that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture, dating back several centuries, that people react to the changes around them by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a boom in these speculations.
“Somewhere else people don’t think about this,” he said.
Mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who teaches courses in the Philippines this year, quickly answered the question of whether he knew about any courses on the “end of the world” there.
“The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world,” he wrote, hinting at an exception from a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years there has been talk of many days of the final judgment, and said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will start to think immediately about the next date" or to philosophize that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period after which the world will end.
Students and teachers are taking the date lightly.
Several said they plan to go to "end of the world" parties.
"Maybe he'll call some friends so we can laugh together," said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
